25|$|Lunar eclipses occur <b>when</b> <b>the</b> <b>Moon</b> {{passes through}} the Earth's shadow. This happens only during a full moon, <b>when</b> <b>the</b> <b>Moon</b> is {{on the far side}} of the Earth from the Sun. Unlike a solar eclipse, an eclipse of the Moon can be {{observed}} from nearly an entire hemisphere. For this reason it is much more common to observe a lunar eclipse from a given location. A lunar eclipse lasts longer, taking several hours to complete, with totality itself usually averaging anywhere from about 30 minutes to over an hour.|$|E
